11 CONFERENCE COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
12 An Act relating to property and critical
infrastructure; creating the Military Installation
13 and Critical Infrastructure Protection Act of 2026;
providing short title; defining terms; prohibiting
14 foreign principals from foreign adversary countries
from owning, having an interest in, or acquiring
15 agricultural land; describing scope of de minimis
indirect interest; directing the sale, transfer, or
16 divestiture of agricultural land under certain
circumstances; establishing registration
17 requirements; allowing for the acquisition of
agricultural land under certain circumstances;
18 deeming contracts, deeds, or other agreements
invalid; assigning the Office of the Attorney General
19 with the responsibility of making certain
determinations; granting the Attorney General the
20 authority to commence certain actions in district
court; providing for the sale of land through
21 judicial foreclosure; providing payment of a reward
to whistleblowers; providing for the disbursement of
22 proceeds; providing for the adoption of rules;
prohibiting foreign principals from foreign adversary
23 countries from purchasing, holding, renting, or
controlling any property near military bases or
24 installations; requiring the sale, transfer, or
Req. No. 4014 Page 1

1 divestiture of property within certain time period;
deeming contracts, deeds, or other agreements
2 invalid; granting the Attorney General the authority
to commence certain actions in district court;
3 providing for the sale of land through judicial
foreclosure; providing payment of a reward to
4 whistleblowers; providing for the disbursement of
proceeds; assigning the Office of the Attorney
5 General with the responsibility of making certain
determinations; establishing guidelines for
6 whistleblowers; providing for referrals to the Office
of the Attorney General; establishing rewards for
7 whistleblowers; setting effective date for
whistleblower enforcement provision; prohibiting
8 entities and governmental entities from entering into
agreements relating to critical infrastructure with
9 foreign principals from foreign adversary countries;
authorizing entities and governmental entities to
10 enter into agreements under certain circumstances;
prohibiting the use of certain software in state
11 infrastructure; providing for the replacement of
prohibited software; providing software removal and
12 notification requirements; directing the Office of
the Attorney General to establish reporting process
13 for non-notified transactions; authorizing the
Attorney General to submit memorandums or reports to
14 certain committee; directing the Attorney General to
retain certain documents and notify the Legislature
15 and Governor; providing for noncodification;
providing for codification; and providing an
16 effective date.
17
18
19 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
20 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law not to be
21 codified in the Oklahoma Statutes reads as follows:
22 This act shall be known and may be cited as the “Military
23 Installation and Critical Infrastructure Protection Act of 2026”.
24
Req. No. 4014 Page 2

1 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 128.1 of Title 60, unless there
3 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 As used in this act:
5 1. “Agricultural land” means a land area that is either arable,
6 under permanent crops, or under permanent pastures. Arable land
7 includes land under temporary crops such as cereals, temporary
8 meadows for mowing or pasture, land under market or kitchen gardens,
9 and land temporarily fallow. Land abandoned as a result of shifting
10 cultivation is excluded. Land under permanent crops is cultivated
11 with crops that occupy the land for long periods and need not be
12 replanted after each harvest, such as orchards or vineyards. This
13 category excludes land under trees grown for wood or timber.
14 Permanent pasture land is land used for five (5) or more years for
15 forage, including natural and cultivated crops;
16 2. “Company” means a for-profit sole proprietorship,
17 organization, association, corporation, partnership, joint venture,
18 limited partnership, limited liability partnership, or limited
19 liability company, including a wholly owned subsidiary, majority-
20 owned subsidiary, parent company, or affiliate of those entities or
21 business associations, that exists to make a profit; or a nonprofit
22 organization;
23 3. “Critical infrastructure” means systems and assets, whether
24 physical or virtual, so vital to Oklahoma or the United States that
Req. No. 4014 Page 3

1 the incapacity or destruction of such systems and assets would have
2 a debilitating impact on state or national security, state or
3 national economic security, state or national public health, or any
4 combination of those matters. A critical infrastructure may be
5 publicly or privately owned and includes, but is not limited to:
6 a. gas and oil production, storage, or delivery systems,
7 b. water supply, refinement, storage, or delivery
8 systems,
9 c. telecommunications networks,
10 d. electrical power generation, transmission, and
11 delivery systems,
12 e. emergency services,
13 f. transportation systems and services, or
14 g. personal data or otherwise classified information
15 storage systems, including cybersecurity;
16 4. “Cybersecurity” means the measures taken to protect a
17 computer, computer network, computer system, or other technology
18 infrastructure against unauthorized use or access;
19 5. “Domicile” means either the country in which a company is
20 registered, where the affairs of the company are primarily
21 completed, or where the majority of ownership share is held;
22 6. “Foreign adversary” means any country designated by the
23 United States Secretary of State as hostile or a Country of
24 Particular Concern (CPC);
Req. No. 4014 Page 4

1 7. “Foreign principal” means:
2 a. the government or any official of the government of a
3 foreign adversary,
4 b. a political party or member of a political party or
5 any subdivision of a political party of a foreign
6 adversary,
7 c. a partnership, association, corporation, organization,
8 or other combination of persons organized under the
9 laws of or having its principal place of business in a
10 foreign adversary, or a subsidiary of such entity, or
11 owned or controlled wholly or in part by any person,
12 entity, or collection of persons or entities of a
13 foreign adversary,
14 d. any person who is domiciled in a foreign adversary and
15 is not a citizen or lawful permanent resident of the
16 United States, or
17 e. any person, entity, or collection of persons or
18 entities, described in subparagraphs a through d of
19 this paragraph having a controlling interest in a
20 partnership, association, corporation, organization,
21 trust, or any other legal entity or subsidiary formed
22 for the purpose of owning real property;
23 8. “Military base or installation” means any land, structure,
24 or property owned or controlled by any division of the United States
Req. No. 4014 Page 5

1 Depa rtment of Defense, Oklahoma National Guard, or any other
2 department of government, state or federal, critical to the safety
3 and security of this state or the United States;
4 9. “Military operating areas” means a military base’s or
5 installation’s military training routes and the airspace established
6 outside of Class A airspace to separate or segregate certain
7 military flight activities from commercial or private aircraft;
8 10. “Non-notified transactions” means foreign investments in
9 the United States that are not voluntarily submitted to the
10 Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States for review
11 under 50 U.S.C., Section 4565;
12 11. “Operational software” means computer programs used for the
13 operation, control, maneuver or maintenance of state infrastructure,
14 or any other computer program applications related to state
15 infrastructure;
16 12. “Software” means any program or routine, or any set of one
17 or more programs or routines, which are used or intended for use to
18 cause one or more computers or pieces of computer related peripheral
19 equipment, or any combination thereof, to perform a task or set of
20 tasks, as it relates to state infrastructure;
21 13. “State infrastructure” means critical infrastructure and
22 transportation infrastructure; and
23 14. “Transportation infrastructure” shall include, but not be
24 limited to:
Req. No. 4014 Page 6

1 a. airports including, but not limited to, commercial and
2 intermodal airports and heliports and all airport
3 infrastructure,
4 b. roadways including, but not limited to, publicly
5 accessible streets, roads, highways, and bridges and
6 all roadway infrastructure including, but not limited
7 to, signage, toll booths, weigh stations, and traffic
8 signals,
9 c. railways including, but not limited to, all classes of
10 freight rail and passenger rail and all railway
11 infrastructure including, but not limited to,
12 intermodal rail yards and signals,
13 d. ports including, but not limited to, inland ports,
14 seaports, deepwater ports, inland waterways, and
15 levees and all port infrastructure including, but not
16 limited to, intermodal stations, and
17 e. public transit including bus, ferry, cable car, tram,
18 trolley, and other types of publicly accessible
19 transportation and all public transit infrastructure.
20 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
21 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 128.2 of Title 60, unless there
22 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
23 A. A foreign principal from a foreign adversary country may not
24 directly or indirectly own, have an interest of greater than twenty-
Req. No. 4014 Page 7

1 five percent (25%) in, or acquire by purchase, grant, devise, or
2 descent agricultural land or any interest, except a de minimis
3 indirect interest, in such land in this state. A foreign principal
4 has a de minimis indirect interest if any ownership is the result of
5 the foreign principal’s ownership of registered equities in a
6 publicly traded company owning the land and if the ownership of the
7 foreign principal in the country is either:
8 1. Less than five percent (5%) of any class of registered
9 equities or less than five percent (5%) in the aggregate in multiple
10 classes of registered equities; or
11 2. A noncontrolling interest in an entity controlled by a
12 company that is both registered with the United States Securities
13 and Exchange Commission as an investment advisor under the
14 Investment Advisers Act of 1940, as amended, and is not a foreign
15 entity.
16 B. A foreign principal that directly or indirectly owns or
17 otherwise controls agricultural land, as defined in Section 1 of
18 this act, in this state shall sell, transfer, or otherwise divest
19 itself of the agricultural land within one hundred eighty (180) days
20 of the effective date of this act.
21 C. A foreign principal that directly or indirectly owns or
22 acquires agricultural land or any interest in such land in this
23 state shall register with the Oklahoma Department of Agriculture,
24 Food, and Forestry within sixty (60) days of the effective date of
Req. No. 4014 Page 8

1 this act or the date of acquisition, whichever is latest. The
2 Department shall establish a form for such registration which, at
3 minimum, shall include all of the following:
4 1. The name of the owner of the agricultural land or the owner
5 of the interest in such land;
6 2. The address of the agricultural land, the parcel
7 identification number of the property appraiser, and the legal
8 description of the property; and
9 3. The number of acres of the agricultural land.
10 D. Notwithstanding the provisions of subsections A and B of
11 this section, a foreign principal from a foreign adversary country
12 may acquire or continue to hold agricultural land on or after the
13 effective date of this act if the foreign principal has a national
14 security agreement with the Committee on Foreign Investment in the
15 United States (CFIUS) as of the effective date of this act or at the
16 time of acquisition and continues to maintain such national security
17 agreement.
18 E. Any current deeds, contracts, rental agreements, or other
19 legal agreements in conflict with the provisions of this act shall
20 be deemed invalid from the date of adoption unless otherwise
21 provided.
22 F. The responsibility for determining whether an entity is
23 subject to the provisions of this section rests solely with the
24 foreign entity, the Attorney General, any qualifying whistleblower,
Req. No. 4014 Page 9

1 and no other individual or entity. An individual or entity who is
2 not a foreign entity shall not be required to determine or inquire
3 whether another person or entity is or may be subject to this
4 section and shall bear no civil or criminal liability under the
5 provisions of this section.
6 G. If a foreign principal from a foreign adversary country does
7 not divest the real property as required by this section, the
8 Attorney General shall commence an action in district court within
9 the jurisdiction of the real property.
10 H. If the real property is held in violation of the provisions
11 of this section, the district court shall order that the real
12 property be sold through judicial foreclosure.
13 I. If a whistleblower referral results in a divestiture of land
14 or other assets held in violation of the provisions of this section,
15 the whistleblower shall be entitled to a reward equal to twenty
16 percent (20%) of the proceeds of the land sale that results from the
17 violation of this section after payments to lienholders. Proceeds
18 of the sale shall be disbursed in the following order, as
19 applicable:
20 1. The payment of authorized costs of the sale, including all
21 approved fees and expenses of the referee and any taxes and
22 assessments due;
23
24
Req. No. 4014 Page 10

1 2. The payment, in an amount approved by the court, to the
2 Office of the Attorney General for reimbursement of investigation
3 and litigation costs and expenses;
4 3. To bona fide lienholders, in their order of priority, except
5 for liens which under the terms of the sale are to remain on the
6 property;
7 4. To whistleblowers; and
8 5. To the restricted foreign entity.
9 J. The Oklahoma Department of Agriculture, Food, and Forestry
10 shall adopt rules to implement the provisions of this section.
11 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
12 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 128.3 of Title 60, unless there
13 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
14 A. A foreign principal from a foreign adversary country shall
15 not be allowed to directly or indirectly purchase, hold, rent, or
16 otherwise control any real property within ten (10) miles of a
17 military base or installation, a military operating area, or other
18 critical infrastructure.
19 B. A foreign principal that directly or indirectly controls any
20 real property covered by the provisions of subsection A of this
21 section, excluding temporary contractual agreements such as rental
22 or lease agreements, shall sell, transfer, or otherwise divest
23 itself of the property within one hundred eighty (180) days of the
24 effective date of this act.
Req. No. 4014 Page 11

1 C. Any current deeds, contracts, rental agreements, or other
2 legal agreements in conflict with this law shall be deemed invalid
3 from the date of adoption unless otherwise provided.
4 D. If a foreign principal from a foreign adversary country does
5 not divest the real property as required by the provisions of this
6 section, the Attorney General shall commence an action in the
7 district court within the jurisdiction of the real property.
8 E. If the real property is held in violation of the provisions
9 of this section, the district court shall order that the real
10 property be sold through judicial foreclosure pursuant to Section
11 125 of Title 60 of the Oklahoma Statutes.
12 F. If a whistleblower referral results in a divestiture of land
13 or other assets held in violation of the provisions of this section,
14 the whistleblower shall be entitled to a reward equal to twenty
15 percent (20%) of the proceeds of the land sale that results from the
16 violation of the provisions of this section after payments to
17 lienholders. Proceeds of the sale shall be disbursed in the
18 following order, as applicable:
19 1. The payment of authorized costs of the sale, including all
20 approved fees and expenses of the referee and any taxes and
21 assessments due;
22 2. The payment, in an amount approved by the district court, to
23 the Attorney General for reimbursement of investigation and
24 litigation costs and expenses;
Req. No. 4014 Page 12

1 3. To bona fide lienholders, in their order of priority, except
2 for liens which under the terms of the sale are to remain on the
3 property;
4 4. To whistleblowers; and
5 5. To the restricted foreign entity.
6 G. The responsibility for determining whether an entity is
7 subject to this section rests solely with the foreign entity, the
8 Attorney General, any qualifying whistleblower, and no other
9 individual or entity. An individual or entity who is not a foreign
10 entity shall not be required to determine or inquire whether another
11 person or entity is or may be subject to the provisions of this
12 section, and shall bear no civil or criminal liability under the
13 provisions of this section.
14 SECTION 5. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
15 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 128.4 of Title 60, unless there
16 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
17 A. Any individual may act as a whistleblower and provide a
18 referral to the Office of the Attorney General for violations of the
19 provisions of Section 3 and Section 4 of this act.
20 B. If a whistleblower referral results in a divestiture of land
21 or other assets held in violation of the provisions of this act, the
22 whistleblower shall be entitled to a reward equal to twenty percent
23 (20%) of the proceeds of the land sale that results from violation
24 of this act.
Req. No. 4014 Page 13

1 C. The whistleblower enforcement provision shall take effect
2 one hundred eighty (180) days after the effective date of this act.
3 SECTION 6. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
4 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 13001 of Title 74, unless there
5 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
6 A. An entity constructing, repairing, operating, or otherwise
7 having significant access to critical infrastructure shall prohibit
8 any foreign principal from having access to critical infrastructure
9 in this state.
10 B. A governmental entity may not enter into a contract or other
11 agreement relating to critical infrastructure in this state with a
12 company that is a foreign principal from a foreign adversary
13 country, or use products or services produced by a foreign principal
14 from a foreign adversary country.
15 C. Notwithstanding the provisions of subsection A and B of this
16 section, an entity or governmental entity may enter into a contract
17 or agreement relating to critical infrastructure with a foreign
18 principal from a foreign adversary country or use products or
19 services produced by a foreign principal from a foreign adversary
20 country if:
21 1. There is no other reasonable option for addressing the need
22 relevant to state critical infrastructure;
23 2. The contract is preapproved by the Office of the Attorney
24 General; and
Req. No. 4014 Page 14

1 3. Not entering into such a contract or agreement would pose a
2 greater threat to the state than the threat associated with entering
3 into the contract.
4 SECTION 7. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
5 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 13002 of Title 74, unless there
6 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
7 A. All software used in state infrastructure located within or
8 serving Oklahoma shall not include any software designed, developed,
9 manufactured, or supplied by a federally banned corporation, nor any
10 software banned at the federal level. All software used in state
11 infrastructure located within or serving Oklahoma shall not include
12 any software designed, developed, manufactured, or supplied by a
13 foreign adversary, a state-owned enterprise of a foreign adversary,
14 or any federally banned corporation or software.
15 B. All software used in state infrastructure in operation
16 within or serving Oklahoma, to include any state infrastructure
17 which is not permanently disabled, shall have all software
18 prohibited by subsection A of this section removed and replaced with
19 software which is not prohibited by subsection A of this section.
20 C. Any state infrastructure provider that removes,
21 discontinues, or replaces any prohibited software shall not be
22 required to obtain any additional permits from any state agency or
23 political subdivision for the removal, discontinuance, or
24 replacement of such software as long as the state agency or
Req. No. 4014 Page 15

1 poli tical subdivision is properly notified of the necessary
2 replacements and the replacement software is similar to the existing
3 software.
4 SECTION 8. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
5 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 13003 of Title 74, unless there
6 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
7 A. The Office of the Attorney General shall establish a process
8 by which local officials, states officials, or other persons may
9 submit information or concerns to the Office regarding non-notified
10 transactions in Oklahoma. The Office of the Attorney General may
11 adopt any necessary rules to implement the provisions of this
12 subsection.
13 B. The Office of the Attorney General may submit a memorandum
14 or report concerning non-notified transactions the Attorney General
15 has identified in Oklahoma to the Committee on Foreign Investment in
16 the United States.
17 C. The Office of the Attorney General shall:
18 1. Retain a copy of any documents submitted to the Committee on
19 Foreign Investment in the United States that are included with a
20 memorandum or report submitted under the provisions of subsection B
21 of this section; and
22 2. Notify the Legislature and the Governor as soon as
23 practicable after submitting a memorandum, report, or other
24
Req. No. 4014 Page 16

1 info rmation pursuant to the provisions of subsection B of this
2 section.
3 SECTION 9. This act shall become effective July 1, 2027.
